      Shadow trading
   =20
 =20
Let=E2=80=99s do some insider trading hypotheticals.=09You are the vice pre=
sident of sales at Amalgamated Widgets Co., a publicly traded company. You =
see, from your sales reports and from your own visits to clients, that Amal=
gamated is having a record-smashing quarter of sales. Everywhere you go, pe=
ople are clamoring to buy as many widgets as you can sell them. You follow =
Amalgamated=E2=80=99s stock closely and you realize that Wall Street analys=
ts and investors have no idea how good this quarter will be, in the widget =
business. Of course you do not rush out and buy Amalgamated stock because t=
hat would be insider trading. But from your own market knowledge you have n=
o doubt that Consolidated Widgets Inc., your closest competitor, will also =
announce a=C2=A0record quarter. Consolidated is also a public company.=C2=
=A0So you buy call options on Consolidated, betting that its stock will go =
up. Is that legal?=09You are the VP of sales at Amalgamated Widgets Co. You=
 have a big pitch with Federated Sprockets Inc., the world=E2=80=99s bigges=
t=C2=A0customer=C2=A0of widgets. Federated buys its widgets exclusively fro=
m Consolidated, and you=E2=80=99ve never even gotten=C2=A0a meeting with th=
em before, but you have finally worked your way in. The pitch goes great. F=
ederated calls you the next day to tell you that they are switching all of =
their business from Consolidated to Amalgamated; there will be a press rele=
ase next week. Of course you do not rush out and buy Amalgamated stock beca=
use that would be insider trading. But you know that this news will be deva=
stating for Consolidated, which is losing its biggest customer. So you buy=
=C2=A0put=C2=A0options on=C2=A0Consolidated, betting that its stock will dr=
op. Is that legal?=09You are the VP of sales at Amalgamated Widgets Co. The=
 chief executive officer calls you into her office and says =E2=80=9Cthis i=
s top secret, but we are in talks to be acquired by Worldwide=C2=A0Hypothet=
ical Products Inc., and we need you to do a due diligence call with the hea=
d of sales at Worldwide.=E2=80=9D You do the call, and the CEO keeps you in=
 the loop for diligence and merger planning. It becomes very clear that the=
 deal is almost done and will be announced next week. Of course you do not =
rush out and buy Amalgamated stock because that would be insider trading. B=
ut from your market knowledge you are pretty sure that this acquisition wil=
l put Consolidated, your closest competitor, in play, and its stock will al=
so go up.=C2=A0So you buy call options on Consolidated, betting that its st=
ock will go up. Is that legal?=09You are the VP of sales at Amalgamated Wid=
gets Co. The chief executive officer calls you into her office and says =E2=
=80=9Cthis is top secret, but we are in talks to acquire Bushwick Artisanal=
 Widget Foundry,=C2=A0and we need you to do a due diligence call with the h=
ead of sales there.=E2=80=9D You do the call, and the CEO keeps you in the =
loop for diligence and merger planning. It becomes very clear that the deal=
 is almost done and will be announced next week. BAWF is also a publicly tr=
aded company.=C2=A0So you buy call options on BAWF, betting that its stock =
will go up when the acquisition is announced. Is that legal?I can tell you =
the answer to Scenario 4, I think. (Nothing here is legal advice!) Under pr=
etty well established U.S. law, this one is illegal. This is called the =E2=
=80=9Cmisappropriation theory=E2=80=9D of insider trading, and the rough id=
ea is that Amalgamated =E2=80=9Cowns=E2=80=9D this information about its me=
rger plans and you have =E2=80=9Cmisappropriated=E2=80=9D it by trading on =
it. In a sense you have front-run Amalgamated, your employer: Amalgamated i=
s looking to buy BAWF stock (in a merger), and you buy it first and then fl=
ip it to Amalgamated (in the merger) for a profit. In theory your front-run=
ning might drive up the price that Amalgamated has to pay, so in an economi=
c sense you really are stealing from Amalgamated.The other three scenarios =
are sort of like that and sort of not. In each of these scenarios, the info=
rmation in some sense belongs to Amalgamated, you learned about it in the c=
ourse of your work for Amalgamated, it is confidential, and you are arguabl=
y =E2=80=9Cstealing=E2=80=9D it to trade Consolidated stock for your own ac=
count. On the other hand, Amalgamated wasn=E2=80=99t planning to trade Cons=
olidated stock, so you aren=E2=80=99t front-running your employer. You are =
just doing an unrelated trade in a different stock using information you go=
t at work.I cannot tell you the answer to the first three scenarios because=
=C2=A0there are no precedents. Which is a kind of answer! Like, the answer =
to the question =E2=80=9Cis this legal,=E2=80=9D for each of those three ca=
ses, is something like =E2=80=9Cummmmmmmmmmm it sounds sketchy but as far a=
s I know nobody has ever gotten in trouble for it?=E2=80=9D That tells you =
something! Perhaps it tells you that nobody has ever done it, but that seem=
s unlikely.=C2=A0Or, rather, that was the answer until last August, when so=
meone got in trouble for it. His name is Matthew Panuwat, and he allegedly =
found himself in essentially Scenario 3: He was the head of business develo=
pment at a mid-sized pharmaceutical company called Medivation Inc., he lear=
ned that Medivation was being acquired, and he went out and bought call opt=
ions on a=C2=A0different mid-sized pharmaceutical company, Incyte Corp.,=C2=
=A0that was an obvious comp for Medivation. (Panuwat allegedly reviewed inv=
estment bank presentations in which =E2=80=9Cthe bankers drew close paralle=
ls between Medivation and Incyte.=E2=80=9D) The merger was announced, Incyt=
e stock went up, and he made money. The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion sued him, and we talked about the case a  couple of  times. People som=
etimes use the term =E2=80=9Cshadow trading=E2=80=9D to describe this sort =
of thing, using inside information about one company to trade the stock of =
a different but correlated company.So now we know that the answer to Scenar=
io 3 is =E2=80=9Cwell, at least the SEC thinks it=E2=80=99s illegal.=E2=80=
=9D The SEC has been wrong before, though, and Panuwat moved to dismiss the=
 case before trial, arguing that this scenario does not amount to insider t=
rading. Earlier this month he lost that motion: A judge ruled that this sce=
nario can be insider trading, and that the SEC can go to trial to try to pr=
ove it. Here is the opinion. The judge, and the SEC, concede that there are=
 no precedents here:It is true that there appear to be no other cases where=
 the material nonpublic information at issue involved a third party. The SE=
C conceded this at oral argument. However, the SEC=E2=80=99s theory of liab=
ility falls within the general framework of insider trading, as well as the=
 expansive language of Section 10(b) and corresponding regulations.=C2=A0Bu=
t insider trading law is pretty broad so sure why not wave it in. But it se=
ems important here that Medivation, Panuwat=E2=80=99s employer, had a very =
broad anti-insider-trading policy that Panuwat was required to sign. It sai=
d (as quoted by the judge):=E2=80=9CDuring the course of your employment . =
. . you may receive important information that is not yet publicly dissemin=
ated . . . about the Company. . . . Because of your=C2=A0access to this inf=
ormation, you may be in a position to profit financially by buying or selli=
ng or in some other way dealing in the Company=E2=80=99s securities . . . o=
r the securities of another publicly traded company, including all signific=
ant collaborators, customers, partners, suppliers, or competitors of the Co=
mpany. . . . For anyone to use such information to gain personal benefit . =
. . is illegal.=E2=80=9DThe way that insider trading law works in the U.S.,=
 under the =E2=80=9Cmisappropriation theory,=E2=80=9D is that you are only =
guilty of insider trading if you misappropriated the information from someo=
ne. (=E2=80=9CInsider trading is not about fairness,=E2=80=9D I  sometimes =
say; =E2=80=9Cit is about theft.=E2=80=9D) If Panuwat had a duty to Medivat=
ion not to trade on the information he got, and he traded on it in breach o=
f that duty, then that was illegal insider=C2=A0trading; if Medivation was =
like =E2=80=9Csure go nuts trade however you want,=E2=80=9D then it was =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0fine? Maybe? In any case the SEC and the judge explicitly refer=
 to this broad policy to support the SEC=E2=80=99s case here. If Medivation=
=E2=80=99s policy had said =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use our secret informatio=
n to trade Medivation securities, or the securities of any other companies =
that=C2=A0we are thinking about acquiring,=E2=80=9D then (1) that would cov=
er pretty much every previous insider trading case and (2) Panuwat would no=
t be in trouble here? But instead it was broad, and he is.One question here=
 is: If you run compliance at a public company, should you take another loo=
k at your company=E2=80=99s insider trading policy?=C2=A0What should it say=
?=C2=A0Here is a client memo from Davis, Polk & Wardwell LLP:The precedenti=
al impact of the case might be limited because of the particular facts alle=
ged by the SEC=E2=80=93namely, a very tight connection between two similarl=
y-sized companies in a focused industry and the fact that the defendant was=
 allegedly told by Medivation=E2=80=99s bankers that Incyte was similarly s=
ituated to Medivation. Nevertheless, this novel insider trading case has dr=
awn attention throughout the securities industry because of its possible im=
plications, and because the SEC=E2=80=99s success on this motion may encour=
age the agency to pursue novel enforcement theories in a variety of areas.P=
ublic companies should note that Medivation=E2=80=99s insider trading polic=
y, which is central to the SEC=E2=80=99s allegations, was broadly worded to=
 cover the use of confidential information to trade the securities of any p=
ublicly traded entity. Public companies may want to review their insider tr=
ading policies in light of the SEC=E2=80=99s focus in this case. Under the =
SEC=E2=80=99s recently proposed rules on Rule 10b5-1 and insider trading, c=
ompanies would be required to disclose whether they have adopted insider tr=
ading policies and procedures that are reasonably designed to promote compl=
iance with insider trading laws.There is something a bit circular here. Med=
ivation=E2=80=99s policy said that using its material nonpublic information=
 to trade other companies=E2=80=99 stocks =E2=80=9Cis illegal,=E2=80=9D and=
 that appears to be true, but it=E2=80=99s true=C2=A0only because it said i=
t.[1] If Medivation=E2=80=99s policy had said =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s perfect=
ly legal to use our material nonpublic information to trade other companies=
=E2=80=99 stocks=E2=80=9D then Panuwat would have a good argument that that=
 was true. The law of shadow trading seems to be =E2=80=9Cit is illegal to =
trade stocks in violation of your company=E2=80=99s insider trading policy,=
 whatever it is.=E2=80=9D So what does it mean for a company to have a poli=
cy =E2=80=9Creasonably designed to promote compliance with insider trading =
laws=E2=80=9D? I think if your policy says =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t insider t=
rade our stock but do whatever you want with other stocks,=E2=80=9D that pr=
obably technically promotes=C2=A0compliance with the laws? And yet I suspec=
t the SEC would be annoyed?Well, what should your policy be, just from a ma=
nagement perspective? I think there=E2=80=99s an argument that it is distra=
cting and disloyal for your executives to use what they learn at work to tr=
ade your competitors=E2=80=99 stocks, and that if they=E2=80=99re doing it =
constantly that might undermine your relationships with customers. (Conside=
r Scenario 2 above: Wouldn=E2=80=99t Federated be annoyed that your reactio=
n to winning its business was to short your competitor=E2=80=99s stock?) Th=
ere is also an argument that your executives develop specialized industry k=
nowledge over the course of a career in the widgets business, and they shou=
ld be allowed to use that knowledge to make intelligent investments,=C2=A0a=
llocate capital to the most promising widgets innovators, etc., and that yo=
u will attract more talented and motivated executives if you allow them to =
profit personally from their industry expertise. If individuals are going t=
o trade stocks, why shouldn=E2=80=99t they trade stocks in businesses they =
know something about? Like the one they=E2=80=99re in?But there=E2=80=99s s=
omething else going on here. The Davis=C2=A0Polk memo continues:In addition=
, investment advisers and broker-dealers frequently maintain restricted tra=
ding lists of companies about which they have obtained material nonpublic i=
nformation. Trading firms should note that the SEC might allege an insider =
trading theory for trading securities of companies other than the company a=
bout which a firm has specific material nonpublic information (e.g., it is =
the subject of a confidential takeover bid) because such information also i=
s alleged to be material to a different company. These firms also might wan=
t to consider whether they have signed a nondisclosure agreement with terms=
 that would cover trading in the securities of companies other than the cou=
nter-party, akin to Medivation=E2=80=99s insider trading policy.Lots of fin=
ancial firms trade public securities but also sometimes get inside informat=
ion. Many hedge funds, for instance, have both public-side activities (buyi=
ng and selling stocks and bonds, etc.) and private-side or =E2=80=9Cwall-cr=
ossed=E2=80=9D activities where they negotiate directly with companies and =
get inside information. A company might want to restructure its debts, and =
will reach out to a big hedge fund that holds a lot of debt and ask it to =
=E2=80=9Cwall-cross=E2=80=9D for a short time to discuss a restructuring. O=
r it might want to do an acquisition and reach out to a big shareholder to =
see if it would put up more money to fund the acquisition, or at least vote=
 in favor. Or an activist investor might win a proxy fight, get board seats=
 at the company, and be privy to inside information as a board member. And =
the hedge fund might sign a confidentiality agreement, agreeing to get nonp=
ublic information about the restructuring or merger or whatever and keep it=
 secret and not trade on it for a defined period, and the company will agre=
e to make the information public after some time so that the hedge fund can=
 trade again (called =E2=80=9Ccleansing=E2=80=9D). And there are ways for a=
ll of this to go wrong or be controversial but it=E2=80=99s all basically u=
nderstood and established practice.Often when this happens the hedge fund w=
ill put the company on some sort of restricted list, so that nobody at the =
fund can trade its stock or bonds. Even if some portfolio manager who=C2=A0=
isn=E2=80=99t involved in the debt restructuring negotiations independently=
 decides she wants to buy some of the company=E2=80=99s stock, the fund won=
=E2=80=99t let her, because the fund has nonpublic information and that=E2=
=80=99s just a bad look.=C2=A0But what do you do after Panuwat?[2] If a ste=
el company calls you up and asks you to take a wall-cross, and you take it,=
 and they say =E2=80=9Cwe are in merger talks and want your support,=E2=80=
=9D you obviously can=E2=80=99t trade that=C2=A0company until the merger is=
 public, but are you also restricted from trading=C2=A0other=C2=A0steel com=
panies? (Car companies?) Is everyone at your fund restricted from trading t=
hose companies? If you are an activist investor and you get a seat on the b=
oard of a retailer, are you prohibited from trading the stocks of=C2=A0othe=
r=C2=A0retailers? If the answers to these questions are =E2=80=9Cyes,=E2=80=
=9D then should you stop accepting wall-crosses and stop seeking board seat=
s? Is the answer =E2=80=9Cwell it depends on how similar the other company =
is to this company=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0How do you tell?I don=E2=80=99t know the =
answers to these questions but, as Davis Polk suggest, they might come down=
 to =E2=80=9Cwhat does your agreement say?=E2=80=9D Like, if you sign a wal=
l-cross agreement[3] that says =E2=80=9Cyou are getting nonpublic informati=
on about Company X, don=E2=80=99t use it to trade Company X stock or any ot=
her stock until you are =E2=80=98cleansed,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D then you might=
 want to restrict every steel company; if it says=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou are get=
ting nonpublic information about Company X, don=E2=80=99t use it to trade C=
ompany X stock until you are =E2=80=98cleansed,=E2=80=99 but for the avoida=
nce of doubt go ahead and trade other similar companies,=E2=80=9D then I gu=
ess you are fine? Is it weird to ask for the agreement to say that? Will th=
e SEC be annoyed? Doesn=E2=80=99t that=C2=A0sound like=C2=A0you=E2=80=99re =
asking to be allowed to insider trade?Also I am not at all=C2=A0sure=C2=A0t=
hat the language of the agreement is the deciding factor. In Panuwat, the f=
irst shadow-trading case ever, the SEC and the judge have emphasized the im=
portance of the fact that Medivation=E2=80=99s insider trading policy speci=
fically prohibited him from trading other companies using corporate informa=
tion. You could imagine the SEC expanding that over time, though, to a more=
 general =E2=80=9Cwell you had to know that it was illegal to use informati=
on about one steel company to trade another one.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0All of this =
stuff is=C2=A0new. Nobody was charged with shadow trading before Panuwat, s=
o nobody quite knows what is allowed and what isn=E2=80=99t. But it is not =
exactly=C2=A0arcane. Knowing secret stuff about some companies in an indust=
ry, while also actively trading other companies in an industry, is a reason=
ably common practice among banks and hedge funds and also individual employ=
ees of those companies. Figuring out whether and when it=E2=80=99s illegal =
is going to be a lot of work.
