      Tontine SPAC
   =20
 =20
Schematically, the way a special purpose acquisition company works is that =
a SPAC sponsor raises, say, $200 million from investors at $10 a share, and=
 then goes out and tries to find a public company to merge with. Let=E2=80=
=99s say she finds a company worth $800 million and agrees to a merger. The=
 post-merger company will be worth $1 billion (the $800 million that the co=
mpany was worth, plus the SPAC=E2=80=99s $200 million pot of cash). Each SP=
AC shareholder will get one share worth $10, for a total of 20 million shar=
es, and the company=E2=80=99s existing shareholders will get 80 million sha=
res.But the SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders get to decide, at the time of the m=
erger, if they want in or not. They can take back their $10 in cash, or the=
y can leave their money in and get back a share of stock in the combined co=
mpany. In my schematic numbers the share was worth $10, so they are indiffe=
rent, but that is never really true. At the peak of the SPAC boom, the shar=
es would be worth $20 or $30 or $80 when the merger closed, and everyone wo=
uld take their shares. Now, SPAC deals are less popular, and it is not unco=
mmon for 95% of a SPAC=E2=80=99s shares to be  redeemed for cash.=C2=A0Merg=
ing with a SPAC can get a company a=C2=A0public listing, but it is a dicey =
way to=C2=A0raise money.So in my schematic example, the SPAC might end up r=
eturning $190 million to its investors. The target company would get $10 mi=
llion. The remaining SPAC shareholders would end up with 1 million shares o=
f the new company, and the target=E2=80=99s existing shareholders would get=
 80=C2=A0million, for a total of 81 million shares. The target company gets=
 a public listing but, after expenses, barely raises any money.[5] It is a =
disappointing outcome.You could imagine tweaking the structure. For instanc=
e, in my example above, the SPAC shareholders got one share for every $10 t=
hey left in the SPAC: If all of the shareholders stayed in the new company,=
 they=E2=80=99d get 20 million shares (for $200 million), but if 95% cashed=
 out then the other 5% would get 1 million shares (for $10 million). What i=
f you changed that math to say that the SPAC shareholders get 20 million sh=
ares=C2=A0no matter what? If they all stay in, then they each get one share=
, nominally worth $10. If 95% redeem, then the other 5% get 20 million shar=
es; each $10 SPAC share would turn into 20 shares of the new company, worth=
 $8.10 each,[6] or $162 total.Obviously if that happened it would be terrib=
le for shareholders of the target company =E2=80=94 who gave away 20% of th=
eir equity for just $10 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the point is that it wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t. If it worked that way you=E2=80=99d be pretty nuts to redeem=
 your stock: Why take back $10 in cash when you could get $162 of stock ins=
tead? Of course these numbers are a bit loose, and you might think that the=
 target company isn=E2=80=99t worth the nominal $800 million valuation, whi=
ch is why you were going to redeem in the first place. But even if you thin=
k the company is worth half as much as advertised, you should take the stoc=
k if everyone else is redeeming. So the equilibrium will be many fewer rede=
mptions, because the more people who redeem, the more stock the remaining p=
eople get, and the less rational it is to redeem.This actual math is I gues=
s too extreme for any real SPACs =E2=80=94=C2=A0what if everyone=C2=A0did=
=C2=A0redeem and you sold 20% of the company to one guy for $10? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but people have tried similar ideas.  Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s big SPAC =
is called Pershing Square Tontine Holdings Ltd., and the =E2=80=9Ctontine=
=E2=80=9D refers to the fact that some of the warrants issued to the SPAC=
=E2=80=99s investors have this sort of the-people-who-stay-divide-up-the-wa=
rrants-of-the-people-who-quit property.And now Gary Cohn=E2=80=99s SPAC is =
doing it, sort of. Last Friday, Cohn Robbins Holdings Corp., a SPAC, announ=
ced a merger with Allwyin Entertainment, a lottery company, with a tontine =
feature:Allwyn=E2=80=99s expected implied pro forma total enterprise value =
of approximately $9.3 billion represents approximately 11.5x 2022E Adjusted=
 EBITDA. However, due to a bonus pool of up to approximately 6.6 million CR=
HC shares to be made available exclusively to non-redeeming CRHC shareholde=
rs, such shareholders have the opportunity to establish ownership stakes at=
 a maximum expected effective valuation multiple of 10.8x 2022E Adjusted EB=
ITDA, or approximately $8.7 billion in total enterprise value. Bonus shares=
 forfeited by redeeming shareholders will be distributed to non-redeeming s=
hareholders on a pro rata basis, which is variable based on a range of exch=
ange ratios for shares held by non-redeeming shareholders of between 1.08x =
and 1.40x, to be determined based on redemptions. =C2=A0Assuming a price of=
 $10.00 per share of CRHC common stock at the closing of the transaction, n=
on-redeeming CRHC shareholders would receive, in exchange for each share of=
 CRHC common stock held, shares of the post-combination company with value =
equating to between $10.80 (assuming no redemptions by CRHC shareholders) a=
nd $14.00 (assuming redemptions resulting in the maximum exchange ratio).It=
=E2=80=99s capped, so it=E2=80=99s not like the non-redeeming SPAC holders =
split a fixed pool of shares;=C2=A0if everyone else redeems, you can only g=
et 1.4 shares for your $10, not millions. Still it=E2=80=99s a nifty idea!
