      Do It Again SPAC
   =20
 =20
Last March, when the SPAC boom was booming,  we talked about Do It Again Co=
rp., which was a proposed SPAC. It fit the SPAC naming conventions of the t=
ime, which were pretty much =E2=80=9Cslap any old name on your SPAC because=
 you can raise money for anything.=E2=80=9D I wrote:To be fair, the It that=
 the Corp. is supposed to Do Again seems to be =E2=80=9Crun a restaurant/re=
tail/franchise business successfully=E2=80=9D rather than just, like, =E2=
=80=9Cdo a SPAC.=E2=80=9D Successfully Build A Public Company Again Corp., =
rather than Tap The SPAC Market For A Bunch Of Money Again Corp. Still ther=
e is some ambiguity. They are planning to raise $125 million. I hope if the=
y succeed they=E2=80=99ll launch a new SPAC in like two weeks, before even =
finding a target for this one. Do Do It Again Corp. Again Corp.=C2=A0It did=
 not do it again, or at all. Today Do It Again Corp. withdrew its registrat=
ion statement. Does this mark the end of the SPAC boom? In various ways, no=
, but still it feels like a symbolic moment. Someone should file a registra=
tion statement for a SPAC called Stop Doing SPACs Corp.
