<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Shadow trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s do some insider trading =
hypotheticals.</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px=
; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are the vice pr=
esident of sales at Amalgamated Widgets Co., a publicly traded company. You=
 see, from your sales reports and from your own visits to clients, that Ama=
lgamated is having a record-smashing quarter of sales. Everywhere you go, p=
eople are clamoring to buy as many widgets as you can sell them. You follow=
 Amalgamated=E2=80=99s stock closely and you realize that Wall Street analy=
sts and investors have no idea how good this quarter will be, in the widget=
 business. Of course you do not rush out and buy Amalgamated stock because =
that would be insider trading. But from your own market knowledge you have =
no doubt that Consolidated Widgets Inc., your closest competitor, will also=
 announce a=C2=A0record quarter. Consolidated is also a public company.=C2=
=A0So you buy call options on Consolidated, betting that its stock will go =
up. Is that legal?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are the VP =
of sales at Amalgamated Widgets Co. You have a big pitch with Federated Spr=
ockets Inc., the world=E2=80=99s biggest=C2=A0<em>customer=C2=A0</em>of wid=
gets. Federated buys its widgets exclusively from Consolidated, and you=E2=
=80=99ve never even gotten=C2=A0a meeting with them before, but you have fi=
nally worked your way in. The pitch goes great. Federated calls you the nex=
t day to tell you that they are switching all of their business from Consol=
idated to Amalgamated; there will be a press release next week. Of course y=
ou do not rush out and buy Amalgamated stock because that would be insider =
trading. But you know that this news will be devastating for Consolidated, =
which is losing its biggest customer. So you buy=C2=A0<em>put=C2=A0</em>opt=
ions on=C2=A0<em>Consolidated</em>, betting that its stock will drop. Is th=
at legal?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are the VP of sales =
at Amalgamated Widgets Co. The chief executive officer calls you into her o=
ffice and says =E2=80=9Cthis is top secret, but we are in talks to be acqui=
red by Worldwide=C2=A0Hypothetical Products Inc., and we need you to do a d=
ue diligence call with the head of sales at Worldwide.=E2=80=9D You do the =
call, and the CEO keeps you in the loop for diligence and merger planning. =
It becomes very clear that the deal is almost done and will be announced ne=
xt week. Of course you do not rush out and buy Amalgamated stock because th=
at would be insider trading. But from your market knowledge you are pretty =
sure that this acquisition will put Consolidated, your closest competitor, =
in play, and its stock will also go up.=C2=A0So you buy call options on Con=
solidated, betting that its stock will go up. Is that legal?</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are the VP of sales at Amalgamated Widgets C=
o. The chief executive officer calls you into her office and says =E2=80=9C=
this is top secret, but we are in talks to <em>acquire</em> Bushwick Artisa=
nal Widget Foundry,=C2=A0and we need you to do a due diligence call with th=
e head of sales there.=E2=80=9D You do the call, and the CEO keeps you in t=
he loop for diligence and merger planning. It becomes very clear that the d=
eal is almost done and will be announced next week. BAWF is also a publicly=
 traded company.=C2=A0So you buy call options on BAWF, betting that its sto=
ck will go up when the acquisition is announced. Is that legal?</li></ol><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can tell you the answer to Scenario 4, I think=
. (Nothing here is legal advice!) Under pretty well established U.S. law, t=
his one is illegal. This is called the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oY=
XJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDE3LzAxLzE4L2luc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy1sYXctYWZ0ZXItc2FsbWFuLw/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9c62daa8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">misappropriation theory</a>=E2=80=
=9D of insider trading, and the rough idea is that Amalgamated =E2=80=9Cown=
s=E2=80=9D this information about its merger plans and you have =E2=80=9Cmi=
sappropriated=E2=80=9D it by trading on it. In a sense you have front-run A=
malgamated, your employer: Amalgamated is looking to buy BAWF stock (in a m=
erger), and you buy it first and then flip it to Amalgamated (in the merger=
) for a profit. In theory your front-running might drive up the price that =
Amalgamated has to pay, so in an economic sense you really are stealing fro=
m Amalgamated.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other three scenarios ar=
e sort of like that and sort of not. In each of these scenarios, the inform=
ation in some sense belongs to Amalgamated, you learned about it in the cou=
rse of your work for Amalgamated, it is confidential, and you are arguably =
=E2=80=9Cstealing=E2=80=9D it to trade Consolidated stock for your own acco=
unt. On the other hand, Amalgamated wasn=E2=80=99t planning to trade Consol=
idated stock, so you aren=E2=80=99t front-running your employer. You are ju=
st doing an unrelated trade in a different stock using information you got =
at work.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I cannot tell you the answer to th=
e first three scenarios because=C2=A0<em>there are no precedents</em>. Whic=
h is a kind of answer! Like, the answer to the question =E2=80=9Cis this le=
gal,=E2=80=9D for each of those three cases, is something like =E2=80=9Cumm=
mmmmmmmmm it sounds sketchy but as far as I know nobody has ever gotten in =
trouble for it?=E2=80=9D That tells you something! Perhaps it tells you tha=
t nobody has ever done it, but that seems unlikely.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Or, rather, that was the answer until last August, when some=
one got in trouble for it. His name is Matthew Panuwat, and he allegedly fo=
und himself in essentially Scenario 3: He was the head of business developm=
ent at a mid-sized pharmaceutical company called Medivation Inc., he learne=
d that Medivation was being acquired, and he went out and bought call optio=
ns on a=C2=A0<em>different </em>mid-sized pharmaceutical company, Incyte Co=
rp.,=C2=A0that was an obvious comp for Medivation. (Panuwat <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0xNTUucGRm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB15d61242" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">allegedly reviewed</a> investment b=
ank presentations in which =E2=80=9Cthe bankers drew close parallels betwee=
n Medivation and Incyte.=E2=80=9D) The merger was announced, Incyte stock w=
ent up, and he made money. The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xNTU/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBb265f1f5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">sued him</a>, and we talked about the case a <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMjMvc3BhYy1zd=
Wl0LWxlYWRzLXRvLXNwYXJjcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVt=
PWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWd=
uPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a11d642" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> couple</a> of =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMjUvaW5za=
WRlcnMtdHJhZGUtaW4tb3V0c2lkZS1jb21wYW5pZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNjIyX01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTI=
2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB948efc0d" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> times</a>. People sometimes use the term =E2=80=9Cshadow trading=E2=80=
=9D to describe this sort of thing, using inside information about one comp=
any to trade the stock of a different but correlated company.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So now we know that the answer to Scenario 3 is =E2=80=
=9Cwell, at least the SEC thinks it=E2=80=99s illegal.=E2=80=9D The SEC has=
 been wrong before, though, and Panuwat moved to dismiss the case before tr=
ial, arguing that this scenario does not amount to insider trading. Earlier=
 this month he lost that motion: A judge ruled that this scenario can be in=
sider trading, and that the SEC can go to trial to try to prove it. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JOeDczMXlwUzc0=
OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc3724cc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here is the opinion</a>.=
 The judge, and the SEC, concede that there are no precedents here:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is true that there appear to be no =
other cases where the material nonpublic information at issue involved a th=
ird party. The SEC conceded this at oral argument. However, the SEC=E2=80=
=99s theory of liability falls within the general framework of insider trad=
ing, as well as the expansive language of Section 10(b) and corresponding r=
egulations.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But insider =
trading law is pretty broad so sure why not wave it in. But it seems import=
ant here that Medivation, Panuwat=E2=80=99s employer, had a very broad anti=
-insider-trading policy that Panuwat was required to sign. It said (as quot=
ed by the judge):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDuri=
ng the course of your employment . . . you may receive important informatio=
n that is not yet publicly disseminated . . . about the Company. . . . Beca=
use of your=C2=A0access to this information, you may be in a position to pr=
ofit financially by buying or selling or in some other way dealing in the C=
ompany=E2=80=99s securities . . . or the securities of another publicly tra=
ded company, including all significant collaborators, customers, partners, =
suppliers, or competitors of the Company. . . . For anyone to use such info=
rmation to gain personal benefit . . . is illegal.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way that insider trading law works in the=
 U.S., under the =E2=80=9Cmisappropriation theory,=E2=80=9D is that you are=
 only guilty of insider trading if you misappropriated the information from=
 someone. (=E2=80=9CInsider trading is not about fairness,=E2=80=9D I <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMTMveW91LWhhdm=
UtdG8tcGF5LXRoZS1yaWdodC1wZXJzb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTI2JnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81d0c840" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> someti=
mes say</a>; =E2=80=9Cit is about theft.=E2=80=9D) If Panuwat had a duty to=
 Medivation not to trade on the information he got, and he traded on it in =
breach of that duty, then that was illegal insider=C2=A0trading; if Medivat=
ion was like =E2=80=9Csure go nuts trade however you want,=E2=80=9D then it=
 was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0fine? Maybe? In any case the SEC and the judge explicit=
ly refer to this broad policy to support the SEC=E2=80=99s case here. If Me=
divation=E2=80=99s policy had said =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use our secret in=
formation to trade Medivation securities, or the securities of any other co=
mpanies that=C2=A0<em>we are thinking about acquiring</em>,=E2=80=9D then (=
1) that would cover pretty much every previous insider trading case and (2)=
 Panuwat would not be in trouble here? But instead it was broad, and he is.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One question here is: If you run complianc=
e at a public company, should you take another look at your company=E2=80=
=99s insider trading policy?=C2=A0<em>What should it say?=C2=A0</em>Here is=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGF2aXNwb2xrLmNvbS9pbnNpZ2h0cy9jbGllbnQtdXBkYXRlL3NlY3Mtc2hh=
ZG93LXRyYWRpbmctY2FzZS1zdXJ2aXZlcy1tb3Rpb24tZGlzbWlzcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBa44024d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">a client memo</a> from Davis, Polk &amp; Wardwell LL=
P:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The precedential impact of t=
he case might be limited because of the particular facts alleged by the SEC=
=E2=80=93namely, a very tight connection between two similarly-sized compan=
ies in a focused industry and the fact that the defendant was allegedly tol=
d by Medivation=E2=80=99s bankers that Incyte was similarly situated to Med=
ivation. Nevertheless, this novel insider trading case has drawn attention =
throughout the securities industry because of its possible implications, an=
d because the SEC=E2=80=99s success on this motion may encourage the agency=
 to pursue novel enforcement theories in a variety of areas.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Public companies should note that Medivation=E2=80=99s in=
sider trading policy, which is central to the SEC=E2=80=99s allegations, wa=
s broadly worded to cover the use of confidential information to trade the =
securities of any publicly traded entity. Public companies may want to revi=
ew their insider trading policies in light of the SEC=E2=80=99s focus in th=
is case. Under the SEC=E2=80=99s recently proposed rules on Rule 10b5-1 and=
 insider trading, companies would be required to disclose whether they have=
 adopted insider trading policies and procedures that are reasonably design=
ed to promote compliance with insider trading laws.</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is something a bit circular here. Medivation=E2=
=80=99s policy said that using its material nonpublic information to trade =
other companies=E2=80=99 stocks =E2=80=9Cis illegal,=E2=80=9D and that appe=
ars to be true, but it=E2=80=99s true=C2=A0<em>only because it said it</em>=
.[1] If Medivation=E2=80=99s policy had said =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s perfectl=
y legal to use our material nonpublic information to trade other companies=
=E2=80=99 stocks=E2=80=9D then Panuwat would have a good argument that that=
 was true. The law of shadow trading seems to be =E2=80=9Cit is illegal to =
trade stocks in violation of your company=E2=80=99s insider trading policy,=
 whatever it is.=E2=80=9D So what does it mean for a company to have a poli=
cy =E2=80=9Creasonably designed to promote compliance with insider trading =
laws=E2=80=9D? I think if your policy says =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t insider t=
rade our stock but do whatever you want with other stocks,=E2=80=9D that pr=
obably <em>technically</em> promotes=C2=A0compliance with the laws? And yet=
 I suspect the SEC would be annoyed?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, =
what should your policy be, just from a management perspective? I think the=
re=E2=80=99s an argument that it is distracting and disloyal for your execu=
tives to use what they learn at work to trade your competitors=E2=80=99 sto=
cks, and that if they=E2=80=99re doing it constantly that might undermine y=
our relationships with customers. (Consider Scenario 2 above: Wouldn=E2=80=
=99t Federated be annoyed that your reaction to winning its business was to=
 short your competitor=E2=80=99s stock?) There is also an argument that you=
r executives develop specialized industry knowledge over the course of a ca=
reer in the widgets business, and they should be allowed to use that knowle=
dge to make intelligent investments,=C2=A0allocate capital to the most prom=
ising widgets innovators, etc., and that you will attract more talented and=
 motivated executives if you allow them to profit personally from their ind=
ustry expertise. If individuals are going to trade stocks, why shouldn=E2=
=80=99t they trade stocks in businesses they know something about? Like the=
 one they=E2=80=99re in?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there=E2=80=99=
s something else going on here. The Davis=C2=A0Polk memo continues:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition, investment advisers and b=
roker-dealers frequently maintain restricted trading lists of companies abo=
ut which they have obtained material nonpublic information. Trading firms s=
hould note that the SEC might allege an insider trading theory for trading =
securities of companies other than the company about which a firm has speci=
fic material nonpublic information (e.g., it is the subject of a confidenti=
al takeover bid) because such information also is alleged to be material to=
 a different company. These firms also might want to consider whether they =
have signed a nondisclosure agreement with terms that would cover trading i=
n the securities of companies other than the counter-party, akin to Medivat=
ion=E2=80=99s insider trading policy.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Lots of financial firms trade public securities but also sometimes =
get inside information. Many hedge funds, for instance, have both public-si=
de activities (buying and selling stocks and bonds, etc.) and private-side =
or =E2=80=9Cwall-crossed=E2=80=9D activities where they negotiate directly =
with companies and get inside information. A company might want to restruct=
ure its debts, and will reach out to a big hedge fund that holds a lot of d=
ebt and ask it to =E2=80=9Cwall-cross=E2=80=9D for a short time to discuss =
a restructuring. Or it might want to do an acquisition and reach out to a b=
ig shareholder to see if it would put up more money to fund the acquisition=
, or at least vote in favor. Or an activist investor might win a proxy figh=
t, get board seats at the company, and be privy to inside information as a =
board member. And the hedge fund might sign a confidentiality agreement, ag=
reeing to get nonpublic information about the restructuring or merger or wh=
atever and keep it secret and not trade on it for a defined period, and the=
 company will agree to make the information public after some time so that =
the hedge fund can trade again (called =E2=80=9Ccleansing=E2=80=9D). And th=
ere are ways for all of this to go wrong or be controversial but it=E2=80=
=99s all basically understood and established practice.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Often when this happens the hedge fund will put the company on=
 some sort of restricted list, so that nobody at the fund can trade its sto=
ck or bonds. Even if some portfolio manager who=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t involved=
 in the debt restructuring negotiations independently decides she wants to =
buy some of the company=E2=80=99s stock, the fund won=E2=80=99t let her, be=
cause the fund has nonpublic information and that=E2=80=99s just a bad look=
.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what do you do after Panuwat?[2=
] If a steel company calls you up and asks you to take a wall-cross, and yo=
u take it, and they say =E2=80=9Cwe are in merger talks and want your suppo=
rt,=E2=80=9D you obviously can=E2=80=99t trade <em>that=C2=A0</em>company u=
ntil the merger is public, but are you also restricted from trading=C2=A0<e=
m>other=C2=A0</em>steel companies? (Car companies?) Is everyone at your fun=
d restricted from trading those companies? If you are an activist investor =
and you get a seat on the board of a retailer, are you prohibited from trad=
ing the stocks of=C2=A0other<em>=C2=A0</em>retailers? If the answers to the=
se questions are =E2=80=9Cyes,=E2=80=9D then should you stop accepting wall=
-crosses and stop seeking board seats? Is the answer =E2=80=9Cwell it depen=
ds on how similar the other company is to this company=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0How d=
o you tell?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know the answer=
s to these questions but, as Davis Polk suggest, they might come down to =
=E2=80=9Cwhat does your agreement say?=E2=80=9D Like, if you sign a wall-cr=
oss agreement[3] that says =E2=80=9Cyou are getting nonpublic information a=
bout Company X, don=E2=80=99t use it to trade Company X stock or any other =
stock until you are =E2=80=98cleansed,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D then you might wan=
t to restrict every steel company; if it says=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou are getting=
 nonpublic information about Company X, don=E2=80=99t use it to trade Compa=
ny X stock until you are =E2=80=98cleansed,=E2=80=99 but for the avoidance =
of doubt go ahead and trade other similar companies,=E2=80=9D then I guess =
you are fine? Is it weird to ask for the agreement to say that? Will the SE=
C be annoyed? Doesn=E2=80=99t that=C2=A0<em>sound like=C2=A0</em>you=E2=80=
=99re asking to be allowed to insider trade?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Also I am not at all=C2=A0<em>sure=C2=A0</em>that the language of the agr=
eement is the deciding factor. In Panuwat, the first shadow-trading case ev=
er, the SEC and the judge have emphasized the importance of the fact that M=
edivation=E2=80=99s insider trading policy specifically prohibited him from=
 trading other companies using corporate information. You could imagine the=
 SEC expanding that over time, though, to a more general =E2=80=9Cwell you =
had to know that it was illegal to use information about one steel company =
to trade another one.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of=
 this stuff is=C2=A0<em>new</em>. Nobody was charged with shadow trading be=
fore Panuwat, so nobody quite knows what is allowed and what isn=E2=80=99t.=
 But it is not exactly=C2=A0<em>arcane</em>. Knowing secret stuff about som=
e companies in an industry, while also actively trading other companies in =
an industry, is a reasonably common practice among banks and hedge funds an=
d also individual employees of those companies. Figuring out whether and wh=
en it=E2=80=99s illegal is going to be a lot of work.</p><table class=3D"li=
