</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schematically, the way a special purpo=
se acquisition company works is that a SPAC sponsor raises, say, $200 milli=
on from investors at $10 a share, and then goes out and tries to find a pub=
lic company to merge with. Let=E2=80=99s say she finds a company worth $800=
 million and agrees to a merger. The post-merger company will be worth $1 b=
illion (the $800 million that the company was worth, plus the SPAC=E2=80=99=
s $200 million pot of cash). Each SPAC shareholder will get one share worth=
 $10, for a total of 20 million shares, and the company=E2=80=99s existing =
shareholders will get 80 million shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bu=
t the SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders get to decide, at the time of the merger,=
 if they want in or not. They can take back their $10 in cash, or they can =
leave their money in and get back a share of stock in the combined company.=
 In my schematic numbers the share was worth $10, so they are indifferent, =
but that is never really true. At the peak of the SPAC boom, the shares wou=
ld be worth $20 or $30 or $80 when the merger closed, and everyone would ta=
ke their shares. Now, SPAC deals are less popular, and it is not uncommon f=
or 95% of a SPAC=E2=80=99s shares to be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/26493398.266627/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMTYvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWRlbWFuZGluZy10aGVp=
ci1zcGFjLW1vbmV5LWJhY2stdG9vLWZhc3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTI2JnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb9d69ac7" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> rede=
emed for cash</a>.=C2=A0Merging with a SPAC can get a company a=C2=A0<em>pu=
blic listing</em>, but it is a dicey way to=C2=A0<em>raise money</em>.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So in my schematic example, the SPAC might end =
up returning $190 million to its investors. The target company would get $1=
0 million. The remaining SPAC shareholders would end up with 1 million shar=
es of the new company, and the target=E2=80=99s existing shareholders would=
 get 80=C2=A0million, for a total of 81 million shares. The target company =
gets a public listing but, after expenses, barely raises any money.[5] It i=
s a disappointing outcome.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagin=
e tweaking the structure. For instance, in my example above, the SPAC share=
holders got one share for every $10 they left in the SPAC: If all of the sh=
areholders stayed in the new company, they=E2=80=99d get 20 million shares =
(for $200 million), but if 95% cashed out then the other 5% would get 1 mil=
lion shares (for $10 million). What if you changed that math to say that th=
e SPAC shareholders get 20 million shares=C2=A0<em>no matter what</em>? If =
they all stay in, then they each get one share, nominally worth $10. If 95%=
 redeem, then the other 5% get 20 million shares; each $10 SPAC share would=
 turn into 20 shares of the new company, worth $8.10 each,[6] or $162 total=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously if that happened it would be te=
rrible for shareholders of the target company =E2=80=94 who gave away 20% o=
f their equity for just $10 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the point is that it=
 wouldn=E2=80=99t. If it worked that way you=E2=80=99d be pretty nuts to re=
deem your stock: Why take back $10 in cash when you could get $162 of stock=
 instead? Of course these numbers are a bit loose, and you might think that=
 the target company isn=E2=80=99t worth the nominal $800 million valuation,=
 which is why you were going to redeem in the first place. But even if you =
think the company is worth half as much as advertised, you should take the =
stock if everyone else is redeeming. So the equilibrium will be many fewer =
redemptions, because the more people who redeem, the more stock the remaini=
ng people get, and the less rational it is to redeem.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">This actual math is I guess too extreme for any real SPACs =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0what if everyone=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>redeem and you sold 20%=
 of the company to one guy for $10? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but people have tried si=
milar ideas. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26493=
398.266627/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAt=
MDYtMjMvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMtYS1tYXR1cmUtdW5pY29ybj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI2MjJ=
